Good news out of LA County: The number of Angelenos who currently have COVID is estimated to be around 1 in 730. The prevalence of the virus hasn't been this low since late October.
LA County has so far administered 1.7 million doses of the COVID-19 vaccine, about half a million of which were second doses.

LA County is reporting 21 new deaths from COVID-19 as well as 943 new cases. Officials say the numbers may be low due to a lag in reporting over the weekend, but still, this is the first time in a long time I can remember the daily case coronavirus count being lower than 1,000.

Ugh. Even though I know how widespread the pain of COVID has been, it's always a shock to hear how it's deeply affected people.

This came up at today's Newsom press conference: Long Beach Mayor Robert Garcia lost both his parents to COVID.

California is reporting 233 new deaths from COVID today, compared to 764 a month ago -- which was the highest death toll ever reported by CA. The state's positivity rate is 3%, compared to 8.9% a month ago. 

Gov. Newsom says he sees "a bright light at the end of the tunnel."
